title: For Sale:  Vltor Mur-1a upper receiver
postcontent: Nearly brand new Vltor Mur-1a upper receiver with forward assist. This considered one of if not the best upper receiver on the market. Vltor CNC-Machines the 7075 Aluminum Forging only after it has been fully stress relieved, and then heat- and cryogenically treated. Each upper is finished by hand and all critical dimensions inspected, and finally given a protective Type III, Class 2 Hard Anodized Finish. It is more rigid and stout then a standard forged upper and being forged it is stronger and more durable then billet receivers. This is perfect for a precision build, hard use build, or for anyone who wants the best of the best. Additionally the forward assist being located further forward makes manipulating an ambi charging handle much easier then standard uppers. The upper has slight anodizing wear were the cam pin indexes and were the charging handle meets this upper which occurs on all upper receivers and is merely cosmetic. This was from mounting it on an upper and cycling a bolt by hand when I first received the upper. It's never had a a barrel or rail installed and the only time it has left the box was the above mentioned time.  Retail is $180 I'm selling for $160. All new ar builds are being put on the back burner so I'd rather see this get put to use rather then sit in my workshop.

This rifle is listed on Gunbrokers. It is not a scam. Just trying to sell to help out my neighbor

THIS IS A UF55 PREFIX ENFIELD No4 MK2 303brit RAF SERVICE RIFLE MANUFACTURED 1955 

This legendary British battle rifle was manufactured at the Royal Ordinance Factory (ROF) at Fazakerley Arsenal Liverpool, England

 It is unissued (new) and includes the original factory issue bayonet. This rifle was made in 1955 and released from ROF as surplus sometime in the late 80's or early 90's. Serial number is A19246.

This is a very rare and great example of this model and type. It was manufactured in 1955 and placed in storage its entire life, up until it was imported by Century Arms International, St Albans, VT (C.A.I) .

This rifle was purchased by my next door neighbor in the 90’s and was wrapped in protective arsenal paper and covered in cosmoline for total protection of all metal parts. He unwrapped it not long after purchasing it and cleaned most of it off. I can still see a small amount on the front sight and blade.

 The bore of the 25” barrel is mint, shiny and in as new unfired and excellent condition.

The black finish is just as it was when packed up in 1955 and the rifle is about as nice as you could find considering that it is a Battle Gun and in the manufacturing process was not handled with the care when it was transferred from station to station. Compared to what someone would expect from the handling of a fine precision rifle.

 The stock is of a lighter wood and shows very nicely. Any bumps or scratches can be viewed in the photos provided in the attached link.

 The over all rifle length is 44 ¾”.

The rifle comes complete with the original bayonet and scabbard which is very sharp. (so care should be taken when handling)

 Finally, the serial numbers on the Receiver, Magazine, Bolt and Wood all match A19XXX.

title: For Sale:  Bulgarian SSR-85C AK
postcontent: Hello, I have a Bulgarian SSR-85C AK for sale.  I have two Bulgarian pre ban 30 round magazines for it. The rifle started out as a single stack with a sporter stock. I had Dave Santurri, a gunsmith in North Attleboro, open up the receiver to accept double stack mags, and used the Bulgarian magazines as a template so they fit perfectly with no wobble. The rifle also has a double stack bolt even though it was a single stack gun. That is how it was imported and is a nice bonus.  I put a set of unissued Soviet laminate wood furniture on it, which is almost impossible to find anymore. Since the gun was imported in a sporting configuration it is 100% Bulgarian and is not pieced together from foreign and US parts. I had to replace a few Bulgarian parts with US parts for 922r compliance since it was no longer in a sporting configuration.  I replaced the trigger with a double hook Tapco G2, it has a Tapco slant muzzle brake and is pinned for Mass. compliance, and the magazines have US made followers and floorplates. All the numbers match and it has a chromed barrel and a chromed bolt carrier. It also has the thicker 1.6mm receiver compared to a normal AK which is 1mm.  Between the price of the rifle, the parts, and the gunsmith charge I have over $1000 in this rifle.  The wood furniture by itself is worth $200.

title: For Sale:  80% lower, milling jig, and carbide end mill bits
postcontent: I'm selling a new %80 lower that is from cerro forge the same forgings used by Colt, Daniel Defense, CMMG, KAC, and numerous other makers. The rear take down pin pocket is already milled which is one of the most difficult areas to mill, this is often called a 95% lower by manufactures. The Jig was purchased new and has been used once and is still completely in spec and comes with three top plates as well as a link to the jig manufactures PDF instructions. One of the top plates has dye on it that was used to ensure the mill didn't make contact with the jig. The jig also has an area milled out to allow the lower to be milled for the teal blue bravo pdq ambi bolt release. The jig features a hardened steel guide pressed in to drill out  the selector switch. Also included is two brand new never used solid carbide extra long shank end mill bits in 1/4" and 3/8". The increased shank allows the user to simply butt up against the top plate, so constant measuring and rechecking isn't necessary. I no longer have access to a mill or drill press so I'm letting theses go. This is essentially a turn key kit for finishing an %80 lower all that is needed is standard size drill bits for the trigger pins and selector. This $250 worth of parts I'm asking $180.

postcontent:
Walther PPS (Police Pistol Slim) is short recoil-operated, locked breech pistol that uses modified Browning-type locking with tilting barrel. Frame of the gun is made from impact-resistant polymer. Trigger is double action only, striker fired, with pre-cocked striker system. This system requires a manual recocking (by partial slide retraction) in the case of misfire. Gun is fitted with automated trigger safety and firing pin block. The removable backstrap of the grip, QuickSafe, offers an additional "storage type" safety; once backstrap is removed, the firing pin is automatically decocked and gun is blocked until the backstrap is reinstalled. Sights are low profile, with rear sight adjustable for windage.

postcontent:
This is an early 1913 dated example of an early Imperial German 1914 pattern Luger as manufactured in late 1913 that has a matching magazine. These DWM pistols exhibited the best fit and finish of the WWI pistols and have an all rust blued finish with straw colored small parts. The top of the chamber area is dated 1913 for the year of manufacture with the front toggle marked "DWM". The upper safety position and extractor are correctly marked "GESICHERT". It is fitted with the standard checkered walnut grips, fixed sights. It is complete with a tin plated magazine with a wooden base that is numbered on the bottom and which matches the pistol.
